  "prompt": "What is the latency on Google Maps traffic updates?",
  "response": "The latency of traffic updates on Google Maps can vary, but generally, Google aims to provide near-real-time traffic data. Typically, traffic information is updated every few minutes, depending on the volume of data collected from users and other sources. \n\nIn urban areas with high traffic density, updates may occur more frequently, while in rural areas, the updates might be less frequent due to fewer data points. Factors that can affect latency include network conditions, the availability of real-time data sources (like incident reports, construction updates, and user-reported conditions), and the specific algorithms Google uses to analyze traffic patterns.\n\nGoogle Maps uses data from a variety of sources, including GPS data from mobile devices, historical traffic information, and reported incidents, to provide accurate and timely updates. However, exact latency figures are not publicly specified by Google.",
